Outliers can exert a considerable influence on the covariance or correlation matrix, which forms a basis for PCA. Therefore, Z-scores method is used for outlier detection and removal. Data points with Z-scores exceeding 3 sigma are flagged as potential outliers and removed from dataframe.

In [61]:
#there are outliers in data, they need to be removed. 
#They can distort the relationships between variables and potentially lead to misleading results.
z_scores=df.apply(zscore)
outliers=(z_scores>3)
df=df[~outliers]

4.2 MOVING WINDOWS CORRELATION¶

In this part, firstly correlation matrix is calculated using corr() function form pandas that calculates the pairwise correlation between columns.By default, df.corr() handles NaN values by excluding them from the calculation. This means that if there are missing values in the data, they will not be considered when computing the correlation coefficients between variables. However, missing values imputation is applied to dataframe to obtain more seamless results as follows: -missing values are interpolated using 'time' option to give more wieght to nearby points and afterwards backwardfilling is applied for the stocks that has no data point at the beginning of timestamp

In [74]:

In order to see how correlations evolve over time, rolling correlations are examined. windows size is set to 26x20. 26 indicates total timestamp number within a day and 20 indicate average day number within a month. So, this windows size shows monthly evaluation. Form the figures, it can be concluded that, although two variables are highly corrleated, it can change if we loofk at its evaluation within a time frame. so, there are months in 2018 for TRKCM and ERGL where they have negative monthly correlations but in general corrleation coeff is above zero as expected.

4.3 PRINCIPAL COMPONENT ANALYSIS¶

PCA will be applied to stock prices to reduce dimensionality. Steps are scaling and appliying PCA. scaling step is important because PCA is sensitive to the scale of the variables. If we do not perform scaling, variables with larger scales can dominate the PCA results.

In [84]:
pca = PCA()

#normalization
scaler=StandardScaler()
normalized_df = scaler.fit_transform(df)

#apply pca
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(normalized_df)

print(f'First principal component: \n {pca_result[1]}')

The explained variance ratios indicate how much of the dataset's overall variability is captured by each individual principal component. When conducting Principal Component Analysis (PCA), components are organized in a way that reflects their respective contributions to the total variance. The first component accounts for the largest portion, followed by the second component, and so on.

In [85]:
explained_variances = pca.explained_variance_ratio_

Loading scores quantify the level of connection between the original variables and the principal components. They reveal the degree to which each variable contributes to the makeup of each principal component. In other words, loading scores show how strongly each variable influences the composition of the derived components in the PCA process.

In [86]:
loading_scores = pca.components_
